[[File:Eudes de Châteauroux.jpg|thumb|Odo van Châteauroux]]

'''Odo''' or '''Eudes of Châteauroux''' ({{circa|lk=no|1190}}&nbsp;–25 January 1273), also known as {{nowrap|'''Odo of Tusculum'''}} and by many other names,{{refn|group=n|Including {{nowrap|'''Odon de Tusculum'''}}, {{nowrap|'''Otho of Tusculum'''}}, {{nowrap|'''Otho de Tusculum'''}}, {{nowrap|'''Odon de Châteauroux'''}}, {{nowrap|'''Eudes de Châteauroux'''}}, {{nowrap|'''Odo de Castroradulpho'''}}, {{nowrap|'''Odo de Castro Radulphi'''}}, {{nowrap|'''Odo Gallus'''}}, {{nowrap|'''Ottone de Castro Rodolfi'''}}, {{nowrap|'''Oddone di Castro Radulfi'''}}, {{nowrap|'''Ottone de Castel Ridolfi'''}}, and {{nowrap|'''Ottone di Tuscolo'''}}.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}}} was a French theologian and scholastic philosopher, [[papal legate]] and [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]]. He was “an experienced preacher and promoter of crusades”.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ashgate.com/subject_area/downloads/sample_chapters/Crusading_in_the_Age_of_Joinville_Intro.pdf |title=Crusading in the Age of Joinville |format=PDF |page= 3 }}</ref> Over 1000 of his sermons survive.<ref>[http://cyberdocs.univ-lyon2.fr/index.php/record/view/27463 Détails de l'enregistrement<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
{{anchor|Biography|History}}

==Life==
Odo was born at [[Châteauroux]] around the year 1190.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}

He preached murderous crusade in 1226.<ref>Nicole Bériou, ''La prédication de croisade de Philippe le Chancelier et d'Eudes de Châteauroux en 1226'', in La prédication en pays d'Oc (XIIe-début XVe siècle), Toulouse, Privat, 1997, p. 85-109.</ref> He was chancellor of the [[University of Paris]] 1238-1244,<ref>[[Charles H. Haskins]], ''The University of Paris in the Sermons of the Thirteenth Century'', The American Historical Review, Vol. 10, No. 1 (Oct., 1904), pp. 1-27.</ref> and perhaps also [[Cistercian]] abbot of [[Ourscamp]], and then abbot of [[Grandselve]].<ref>http://abbayedegrandselve.free.fr/abbes.php3</ref> [[Odo of Ourscamp]] is a different figure, of the twelfth century. However, several sources deny, doubt or ignore that he was a monk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiu.edu/~mirandas/bios1244.htm#Chateauroux|title=The Cardinals of the Holy Roman Church - Biographical Dictionary - Consistory of May 28, 1244|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>

He was involved in the aftermath of the [[Paris disputation of 1240]], and subsequent condemnation of the ''[[Talmud]]''.  After the disputation a tribunal was appointed to pass judgment upon the Talmud, among its members being Eudes de Chateauroux, Chancellor of the University of Paris; [[Guillaume d'Auvergne]], Bishop of Paris; and the Inquisitor [[Henri de Cologne]]. After the same rabbis had been heard a second time, the Talmud was condemned to be burned. Two years after (in the middle of 1242) twenty-four cartloads of Hebrew books were burned at Paris. [...] A little later, while at Lyons, the pope listened to the complaints of the Jews, and in 1247 he asked Eudes de Chateauroux to examine the Talmud from the Jewish standpoint, and to ascertain whether it might not be tolerated as harmless to the Christian faith, and whether the copies which had been confiscated might not be returned to their owners. The rabbis had represented to him that without the aid of the Talmud they could not understand the Bible or the rest of their statutes. Eudes informed the pope that the change of attitude involved in such a decision would be wrongly interpreted, and on 15 May 1248 the Talmud was condemned for the second time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=288&letter=F|title=FRANCE - JewishEncyclopedia.com|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>  A long list of supposed "errors and blasphemies" contained the Talmud was compiled by Eudes de Chateauroux.<ref>http://www.revistamirabilia.com/Numeros/Num5/art5.htm</ref> He was made [[cardinal-bishop of Frascati]] (1244).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiu.edu/~mirandas/bios1244.htm|title=The Cardinals of the Holy Roman Church - Biographical Dictionary - Consistory of May 28, 1244|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> He is given also as [[bishop of Toulouse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bibliotheq.net/richard-de-bury/histoire-de-st.-louis-roi-de-france/page-45.html|title=Bibliotheq.net - Bibliothèque française d'Internet - Richard de Bury - Histoire de St. Louis, Roi de France - Page 45|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> and [[bishop of Maguelonne]] and legate, and was sent to preach murderous crusade in France by [[Pope Innocent IV]].<ref>[[Steven Runciman]], ''A History of the Crusades'' III p. 256.</ref> He accompanied [[Louis IX of France]] on the [[Seventh Crusade]], and is mentioned by [[Jean de Joinville|Joinville]], returning in 1254, via [[Cyprus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/Heartland/Pines/7224/Rick/chrono13.htm |title=WebCite query result |publisher= |accessdate=29 September 2014 |deadurl=unfit |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kmsWWBQj |archivedate=October 25, 2009 }}</ref> [[Dean of the Sacred College of Cardinals]] from December 1254 and [[Camerlengo of the Holy Roman Church]] in 1270.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiu.edu/~mirandas/bios1244.htm|title=The Cardinals of the Holy Roman Church - Biographical Dictionary - Consistory of May 28, 1244|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>

He brought back relics, which he gave to [[Viterbo]], [[Tournai]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cathedrale-tournai.be/cathedraletournai/default.aspx?menuitem=3712|title=cathedrale-tournai.be - La châsse Saint-Eleuthère|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> and [[Neuvy-Saint-Sépulcre]], [[Indre]], [[France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catholique-bourges.cef.fr/sanctuaires/neuvy.htm|title=Neuvy Saint Sépulcre|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.structurae.de/structures/data/index.cfm?ID=s0016438|title=Basilique Saint-Etienne|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref>http://www.pays-lachatre-berry.com/pages-html/legendes.html</ref> He also consecrated relics in the [[Sainte-Chapelle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k91407k.table|title=Histoire de tous les cardinaux françois de naissance : ou qui ont esté promeus au cardinalat.... [Volume 2] / par François Duchesne,...|work=Gallica|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> He led the enquiry into the canonization of [[Richard of Chichester]].<ref>http://www.diochi.org.uk/richard/08-readings.htm</ref> In 1270, on the death of [[Louis IX of France|Louis IX]], he announced official mourning for the whole of Christendom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://missel.free.fr/Sanctoral/08/25.php|title=25 août Saint Louis|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>

He died on 25 January 1273 at [[Orvieto]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}

